        <h1 class="home-title">Lee Wilkers</h1>
        <p class="home-identity-terms"><em><span class="home-place-note home-cite-note" tabindex="0">realist management<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-cite-prose">Managing what is rather than what should be &ndash; attending to the actual work, actual constraints, actual people, rather than the plan&rsquo;s idealizations. Weick framed organizations as continuous sense-making in the face of equivocal information, where managers act first and figure out the meaning afterward.<sup>1</sup> Sch&ouml;n located professional knowledge in reflection-in-action: practitioners generate understanding through experimentation in specific situations, not by applying pre-formed theory.<sup>2</sup></span><span class="home-cite-refs"><span><sup>1</sup>&nbsp;Weick, <em>Sensemaking in Organizations</em>, Sage, 1995.</span><span><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;Sch&ouml;n, <em>The Reflective Practitioner</em>, Basic Books, 1983.</span></span></span></span></em>, <em><span class="home-place-note home-cite-note" tabindex="0">useful disagreement<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-cite-prose">Treating friction as information &ndash; the gaps between what people and organizations say, what they do, and what they want are usually the design work. Hirschman distinguished voice (raising the disagreement) from exit (leaving silently), and argued that organizations decline when voice is suppressed.<sup>1</sup> Argyris and Sch&ouml;n named the deeper move: organizations defend against productive disagreement through single-loop error-correction; genuine inquiry requires double-loop learning, which surfaces the governing assumptions behind the error.<sup>2</sup></span><span class="home-cite-refs"><span><sup>1</sup>&nbsp;Hirschman, <em>Exit, Voice, and Loyalty</em>, Harvard University Press, 1970.</span><span><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;Argyris &amp; Sch&ouml;n, <em>Organizational Learning</em>, Addison-Wesley, 1978.</span></span></span></span></em>, <em><span class="home-place-note home-cite-note" tabindex="0">strategic unplanning<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-cite-prose">The careful undoing of a design that is no longer the right design, made with the people the design will touch. Mintzberg distinguished deliberate strategy from emergent strategy.<sup>1</sup> Lindblom argued that policy advances by successive limited comparisons rather than rational-comprehensive design.<sup>2</sup> Sch&ouml;n located professional practice in the swampy lowlands rather than on the high ground of technical rationality.<sup>3</sup></span><span class="home-cite-refs"><span><sup>1</sup>&nbsp;Mintzberg, &ldquo;Crafting Strategy,&rdquo; <em>Harvard Business Review</em>, 1987.</span><span><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;Lindblom, &ldquo;The Science of &lsquo;Muddling Through,&rsquo;&rdquo; <em>Public Administration Review</em>, 1959.</span><span><sup>3</sup>&nbsp;Sch&ouml;n, <em>The Reflective Practitioner</em>, Basic Books, 1983.</span></span></span></span></em></p>
      </header>
      <p class="home-lede home-lede-greeting">Hi, I&rsquo;m Lee &ndash; an independent consultant based in <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="the global health capital of the world; i&rsquo;ve worked with most major institutions in the area">Atlanta</span>.</p>
      <section class="home-section home-history-section" aria-label="Background">
        <p class="home-history">Most of my work has been in and around public health and global health ethics, with formative detours through <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="complex adaptive systems">ecology</span> and <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="A complex adaptive service">hospitality</span>.</p>
        <p class="home-history">For a decade+ I&rsquo;ve helped organizations understand and design for the human capacities, potential, and interests that our usual ways of working tend to miss.</p>
        <p class="home-note-label home-history-fields">Health / Science / Policy / Public interest</p>
        <p class="home-history">Raised in the <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="the data center capital of the world &ndash; we lived a few miles from the fiber carrying most of the world&rsquo;s web traffic">DC area</span>, closer to cattle than the Capitol; Studied ecology along the James River in <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="Virginia Commonwealth University">Richmond, Virginia</span>, and public health in <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="Rollins (Emory)">Atlanta, Georgia</span>.</p>
      </section>

